Hi Hubas,

Thank you very much for your work, it's absolutely great .-) and sorry
for the delay, I've been really busy last weeks.

On Mon, 2006-02-06 at 23:57 +0100, Hubai Tamas wrote:
> -----BEGIN PGP SIGNED MESSAGE-----
> Hash: SHA1
> 
> Nicolas Boichat wrote:
> > Could you please try to put the attached file in db/monitor ?
> > 
> > I should add support for your monitor. However, some controls looks
> > strange so it would be very nice if you could check that all controls
> > work.
> 
> Ok, I've checked them.
> 
> There is an error message occuring quite often which states that the
> first byte of a response is 0x51 while it should be 0x6e. Therefore I
> think 0x6e should also be accepted after finding out what makes the
> difference.

It's hard for me to understand what happens. Could you please send me
the whole output when an error occurs (not only the error) ? Please run
ddccontrol with "-v -v" parameters so you get many debug infos. I
suspect the error may come from a second part of the EDID, but I need
more data. Thanks.

> Most of the controls identified in the xml are correct, however some
> differ in the list of possible options. Also, I've identified some of
> them but there are still some obscure ones. I didn't make any change to
> the xml yet, I think you should review them first and possibly give some
> advice on the remaining ones.

I modified the database, and commited it to the CVS (so please do a "cvs
update"), your detailled report was very very useful and clear .-)

May I put your report in the documentation on the website ? I think it
could be useful in the future, for me and other developpers.

Some remarks on you report :

[snip]
> summary of controls
> --------
> 
> osd controls without corresponding ddc/ci controls:
> (or at least, setting them does not modify any ddc/ci controls)
> 
>   osd/h-position   (horizontal position of osd, 0-100)
>   osd/v-position   (vertical position of osd, 0-100)

It's amazing these controls are not supported... I feel they are rather
important...

>   osd/transparency (boolean specifying whether osd is translucent)
>   osd/display time (idle time before osd closes, chosen from
>                     5 sec, 10 sec, 20 sec and 200 sec)
>   information      (tells the horizontal and vertical frequency,
>                     screen resolution and 'PP' (which I don't know))
> 
> list of ddc/ci controls:
> (controls are identified by their hex id and xml name if present)

[snip]

> 0x60 inputsource (?)
>   reported range 0-3, but sticked to 1, readonly
>   based on the xml files for other models, this should
>   select input source (1 for analog, 3 for digital)
>   but for this model, only analog input (1) is available
>   TODO: check

I removed it from the XML file.

> 0x62 UNKNOWN
>   setting, 0-50, regular
>   factory default for this setting is 25
>   after tweaking some other settings, it changed to 30
>   (I don't know the exact setting that changed it)
>   so it must be of some use, but I'm unable to find out
>   TODO: find out

We probably will never know what it means .-) Probably an engineering
control, at least it is not in the CAPS string so not designed to be
modified by the user.

> 0x6c UNKNOWN
>   setting, 0-255, transient -> 255
>   TODO: find out
> 
> 0x6e UNKNOWN
>   setting, 0-255, transient -> 255
>   TODO: find out
> 
> 0x70 UNKNOWN
>   setting, 0-255, transient -> 255
>   TODO: find out
> 
> # values 0x6c, 0x6e, 0x70 make me feel that they are an RGB triplet
> # xml comments state service RGB black levels
> # however, I haven't noticed any effects

Lots of monitors have these controls, but I've never seen any effect.

> 0x87 NEW sharpness
>   setting, 0-25, regular
>   osd path: image/sharpness
>   this option isn't present in any of the SAM####.xml's
>   specifies the sharpness of the monitor, higher means sharper
>   when set below 10, screen is blurred
>   when set near 25, light objects get dark contours and vice versa
>   FIX: add this setting

Added.

[snip]

> 0xca osd
>   setting, 1-2, transient -> 2
>   this setting disables the display of the osd panel
>   however, the buttons work the same way
>   (i.e. the menu can be still controlled if you remember the positions)
>   if the menu is already displayed, it isn't removed but does
>   not reappear after hiding
>   also, if the menu is active but not shown, it does not show up
>   when turned on, only after closing and reopening it
>   though this option is present in the xml file,
>   ddccontrol seems not to recognise it
>   FIX: make this available

I used 0xf5 for osd lock, which is more useful, I did not create an
entry for this one.

> 0xcc language
>   setting, 1-11, persistent
>   osd path: osd/language
>   changing this setting switches back to first page of osd
>   2 -> english (English)
>   3 -> french (Franais)
>   4 -> german (Deutsch)
>   5 -> italian (Italiano)
>   9 -> russian ()
>   10 -> spanish (Espaol)
>   11 -> swedish (Svenska)
>   8 does nothing (keeps the old value), similarly to out-of-range values
>   1, 6 and 7 map to 2 (english)
>   changing this setting (even identically) saves all
>   settings using 0xb0/1 (but monitor led does not blink)
>   besides making this setting persistent, this also means that
>   other changes meant to be transient are also saved
>   this is a perhaps unwanted side-effect

Great, you even found a bug in Samsung's hardware .-)

>   throws IR (except for 0 and 8 which do nothing)
>   TODO: IR

I also fixed the language list.

> 0xdc magicbright
>   setting, 1-4, regular
>   1 -> text
>   2 -> internet
>   3 -> entertain
>   4 -> custom
>   it is strange that values higher than 4 are permitted and kept,
>   despite the reported maximum of 4
>   in these modes, none of the options has a tick next to it
>   on the osd magicbright box
>   FIX: correct the list of options

Fixed.

> 0xe0 colorpreset
>   setting, 0-3, regular
>   0 -> normal or custom
>   1 -> warm
>   2 -> cool
>   3 maps to 0
>   osd values 'normal' and 'custom' seem to be impossible to
>   distinguish using this control
>   when writing a value of 0 (or 3), it sets mode to custom (on osd)
>   and recalls the last custom mode superceded by normal/warm/cool
>   (if the control was not already set to 0)
>   I found no way to reset to normal using this control
>   (setting r/g/b to 32/32/32 has the same effect but the osd
>   still says 'custom')
>   setting this also modifies values @ 0x16, 0x18, 0x1a
>   also, setting those values sets this preset to 0 (custom)
>   FIX: correct the list of options

Fixed.

> 0xe1 power
>   setting, 0-1, difficult to tell whether it is persistent :D
>   monitor power (on/off)
>   has the same effect as the soft-off button on the monitor face
>   0 -> off
>   1 -> on
>   while listed in the xml, ddccontrol still does not recognize it
>   throws IR
>   FIX: make it recognized
>   TODO: IR

This control is surprisingly not in CAPS string. I forced it to be
enabled.

> 0xe2 UNKNOWN
>   setting, 0-1, persistent
>   this setting is persistent, but doesn't affect others
>   it has to do something with the dirty flag
>   when in state 0, slow auto adjust (0x1e/1) takes approx. 4.5 seconds
>   when in state 1, slow auto adjust (0x1e/1) takes approx. 2 seconds
>   timing of fast auto adjust (0x1e/2) seems unaffected
>   if the dirty flag is turned on (using 0x04 or 0x06), an auto
>   adjustment takes place on the next off+on or resolution change
>   which turns the dirty flag back off
>   if, however, this setting is set to 1 before the off+on or
>   resolution change, the dirty flag is not processed
>   that is, the auto adjustment does not occur and the status of
>   the dirty flag is kept
>   when it is reset to 0, if the dirty flag is on, the auto adjustment
>   takes place on the next off+on or resolution change
>   (it this setting is not reset to 1 meanwhile)
>   TODO: check if it's the real and only effect

I think it is an engineering VCP, so I don't think we need to support it
(not in CAPS).

> 0xed UNKNOWN
>   setting, 0-255, transient -> 99
>   TODO: find out
> 
> 0xee UNKNOWN
>   setting, 0-255, transient -> 101
>   TODO: find out
> 
> 0xef UNKNOWN
>   setting, 0-255, transient -> 101
> 
> # similarly to values 0x6c, 0x6e, 0x70, these values
> # (0xed, 0xee, 0xef) make me feel that they are an RGB triplet
> # xml comments state SAM RGB black levels
> # however, I haven't noticed any effects

Same comment as for RGB black level.

> 0xf0 UNKNOWN
>   readonly (set to 3, reported max is 0)
>   according to the xml, this is supposed to be the magiccolor
>   setting for models that support it
>   actually, this model does not
>   the reported max is still quite strange
>   TODO: check whether it's really magiccolor & why is max < value

This often happens with RO controls, don't worry .-)

> 0xf2 gamma
>   setting, 0-2, regular
>   osd path: color/gamma
>   0 -> mode1
>   1 -> mode2
>   2 -> mode3
>   FIX: correct the list of options

Fixed. May you try to find out what gamma values do the values
represent ? Just "high", "normal" and "low" are fine for me (it may be
complicated to compute real gamma value). This page could help:
http://www.normankoren.com/makingfineprints1A.html#gammachart .

> 0xf5 NEW buttons
>   setting, 0-2, transient
>   0 monitor face buttons are fully functional
>   1 osd can't be opened, pressing any button on the monitor face
>     (except for soft-off) displays a 'MagicTune' popup instead
>     of its regular function
>     used by official utility to avoid changing the settings on the
>     osd while it is running
>     it control 0xca is used to disable the osd, this function
>     will disable the buttons with no popup when they are pressed
>   2 maps to 0
>   FIX: add this setting

Added.

> thanks
> --------
> Finally, let me thank the authors of ddccontrol for creating this
> great software for the linux community, filling the gap for a
> MagicTune port.

Thank you, and thanks to the impressive open source community, which
gives very valuable feedbacks.

> I really like the command-line support which is
> even missing from the proprietary, Windows-only version.

Windows and command-line are not good friends .-)

Thanks again,

Best regards,

Nicolas



