Of course you may. I don't know what's its usefulness once the data went to=
=20
the program, but I'm so glad with ddccontrol that you may add even my=20
girlfriend when I'll have one. I'll report it here.


> Yes it's slow, I know about this... The slow part is, I think, ddcpci
> initialisation. You may try is to disable ddcpci at compilation time
> (./configure --disable-ddcpci), update to the latest nvidia drivers (I
> don't remember the exact version), which support /dev/i2c-* devices,
> load the i2c-dev kernel module. I think it should be faster.

Right, that is solved too. I had already the latest nVidia drivers (1.0-876=
2)=20
with i2c support, and with a plain "./configure", dcccontrol detected both=
=20
pci and i2c paths, but the latter didn't work because I had to set things=20
right. In case any other user has the same problems, I think that mine ones=
=20
came from:

=A0a) Messing a lot with kernel modules and ddccontrol broke i2c sometimes.
=A0c) I wasn't aware that /dev/i2c-* files are r-w for root only.
=A0b) I hadn't identified the right device (here it is dev:/dev/i2c-4)

Now I have no problem with the normal install in a fresh X-session when=20
running as root
=A0# ddccontrol -r 0x72 -w 80 dev:/dev/i2c-4
And after a quick
=A0# chmod +s /usr/bin/ddccontrol
a normal user can also run it [surely an entry in /etc/sudoers would be a=20
better idea].


The i2c way is three times faster than pci, and ~0.60 sec/write is enough f=
or=20
my fun. Anyway, if it were easy to implement someday, I'd suggest a kind of=
=20
